	voicesCreditHtml={`Photos via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Wikimedia Commons</a> &mdash; Andrew Murray, George MacDonald, and Charles Spurgeon (all public domain).`}
	wordHeading={`His Word will not return void`}
	wordBodyHtml={`<p>You might not feel different the first time you read it. That's okay. The Father's love isn't a pre-game hype feeling — it's a foundation, and foundations get built quietly, one day at a time. Every verse you take in is your Father planting something in you that no loss can take and no win can inflate.</p><p class="mt-4" style="color: var(--color-ink);">"My word… will not return to me empty, but will accomplish that which I purpose." <span style="color: var(--color-muted);">— Isaiah 55:11</span></p>`}
	fatherSaysHeading={`What your Father says over you`}
	fatherSaysHtml={`<p>"I know the pressure you carry onto that field. I see the nerves before the whistle, the mistake you keep replaying, the fear of letting everyone down. And I want you to hear Me over the roar of the crowd: you are Mine, and I love you right now — not the winning you, not the record-setting you. You.</p><p>I'm not keeping score against you. I don't love you more on the days you win or less on the days you lose. I made you on purpose, and I called you wonderful before you ever competed. When the scoreboard says you failed, come to Me — I'll renew your strength and remind you who you really are. You don't have to perform for Me. You just have to come. I'm your Father, I delight in you, and no game on earth can change that."</p>`}
	prayerHeading={`A prayer for athletes`}
	prayerHtml={`<p>Our Father, we thank You and praise You for these athletes — every competitor carrying more than the crowd ever sees. Let them hear Your whisper above the roar of the crowd and the verdict of the scoreboard. Let them encounter Your love — not as a rule, but as a Father's delight — and know they are Your beloved son or daughter, not a performer, apart from any win or loss.</p><p>Father, You delight over them whether they finish first or last. Steady them in the pressure, give them teammates who point them to You, and carry them through the long recoveries and the hard losses when they feel like they're not enough. I pray Your protection over them — from injury and from the fear of it, from the idol of performance, from the lie that they are only as good as their last game, from the loss of identity when the season ends, and from the enemy who would steal their joy. Guard their bodies and their hearts.</p><p>Let them know there is no condemnation in You when they fail, that they are fearfully and wonderfully made, and that nothing — no defeat, no injury, no ending — can separate them from Your love. Let them know You, their Father, as their true reward, greater than any crown that fades. And may they wake up every single day knowing they are loved by their heavenly Father.</p><p>In Jesus' name, amen.</p>`}
